      "SummaryText": "led in all gas houses where flammable gas is transferred to aerosol containers. These systems are designed to detect and extinguish an ignition before a catastrophic explosion can occur.\n- All storage tanks that store hazardous materials are inspected on a periodic basis.\n- Periodic inspections are performed to ensure that all process equipment is adequately grounded. This reduces the chance of hazardous static electricity discharge that could ignite flammable vapors.\n- Tankers are equipped with emergency shutdown capability, adding to the safety of the unloading process.\n- Pressure relief valves are installed on the storage tanks and piping systems.\n- Standardized operating procedures are utilized for unloading and handling of flammable materials.\n- Ventilation systems are installed to prevent the accumulation of flammable vapors in processing areas.\n- A deluge fire suppression system is installed in the propellant tank farm to reduce the risk of a major fire or explosion.\n\nFIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY: \nThere have been no accidents or injuries related to the covered process during the past five years.\n\nEMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM: \nThe Accra-Pac, Inc. DBA Voyant Beauty \"Contingency Plan and Emergency Procedures\" has been developed in concert with the Elkhart Fire Department and Elkhart County Local Emergency Planning Committee. The plan addresses fire, explosion, spills and releases of chemicals, severe weather, and other criteria. The plan details actions to be taken by Accra-Pac, Inc. DBA Voyant Beauty for such emergencies, safety equipment, communication responsibilities, and coordination with off-site responders. The Accra-Pac, Inc. DBA Voyant Beauty emergency response program is based on the OSHA requirements for Emergency Action Plans (29 CFR 1910.38 and 1910.119), RCRA Contingency Plan (40 CFR 265.5) and HAZWOPER (29 CFR 1910.120). We have trained our employees for emergency response action and maintain a written response plan. The plan has been coordinated wi"
